==Urdu translation==
The ''Urdu Encyclopaedia of Islam''  is the project of translating the Encyclpedia of Islam into [[Urdu]].
It was started in the 1950s at [[University of the Punjab]], as a project led by Muhammad Shafi.<ref>
{{cite book|title=Islamic culture &amp; civilization in Pakistan|author=Abdur Rauf|publisher=Ferozsons|year=1975|pages=139|chapter=''The Urdu Encyclopaedia of Islam''}}
{{cite book|title=Scholarly publishing in Asia: proceedings|editor=Shigeo Minowa and Amadio Antonio Arboleda|publisher=University of Tokyo Press|year=1973|chapter=''Urdu Encyclopaedia of Islam''|pages=70 et seq.}}{{cite book|title=Asia: Asian quarterly of culture and synthesis|publisher=Imprimerie d'Extrême-Orient|year=1954|volume=4|pages=633|chapter=Encyclopaedia of Islam Pakistan's Venture}}
{{cite web|title=Department of ''Urdu Encyclopaedia of Islam'' at the University of the Punjab|url=http://pu.edu.pk/home/department/36/Department-of-Urdu-Encyclopaedia-of-Islam}}
</ref>  The editorial board worked on translating the Leiden ''Encyclopaedia'' into Urdu, amending, correcting, and adding to the Leiden text themselves.<ref name=IS>{{cite book|title=Islamic studies|publisher=Central Institute of Islamic Research (Pakistan)|year=1963|pages=141|volume=2}}</ref>
The original plan for publication, as laid out by Shafi and others, was for the ''Encyclopaedia'' (which was to be entitled ''Urdu Da’ira Ma’arif-i-Islamiya'') to span between 20 and 22 volumes, with roughly a hundred illustrations per volume, published at a rate of four volumes per year.<ref>{{cite book|title=UNESCO bulletin for libraries|publisher=[[United Nations Educational, Scientific, and Cultural Organization]]|year=1954|volume=8|pages=62}}</ref>
At the time of Shafi's death in 1963, one volume of the encyclopaedia had been published (in February 1954), and a second volume was in press.<ref name=IS /><ref>{{cite book|title=Journal of the Pakistan Historical Society|publisher=Pakistan Historical Society|year=1963|volume=11&ndash;12|pages=264}}</ref>
Because of Shafi's death, and lack of funding, work on the ''Encyclopaedia'' stalled until 1971, when a grant from the [[Asia Foundation]] enabled it to resume.<ref>{{cite book|title=Islamic Culture: The Hyderabad Quarterly Review|author=Islamic Culture Board|chapter=Urdu Encyclopaedia of Islam|publisher=Deccan|year=1971|pages=79|volume=36}}</ref>  Volumes 10 and 12 were completed by 1973.<ref>{{cite book|title=Year Book|publisher=Pakistan Education Division|year=1973|pages=22}}</ref>
By 1985, 21 out of a planned 25 volumes had been published.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Muslim World|author=World Muslim Conference|publisher=Motamar al-Alam al-Islami; World Muslim Congress|year=1985|volume=23|issue=1&ndash;26|pages=32|chapter=Urdu Encyclopaedia of Islam}}</ref>

