'''Granaína''' ({{IPA-es|ɡɾanaˈina}}) is a [[flamenco]] [[palo (flamenco)|style]] of singing and [[guitar]] playing from [[Granada]]. It is a variant of the [[fandangos|Granada fandangos]]. It was originally danceable, but now has lost its rhythm, is much slower, and is usually only sung or played as a guitar solo, reflecting its Arab-Moorish heritage more strongly than other fandangos.<ref>{{cite book|editor=Claus Schreiner|title=Flamenco: Gypsy Dance and Music from Andalusia|year=1990|publisher=Amadeus Press|location=Portland, OR|page=72}}</ref>

The famous singer ''Don'' [[Antonio Chacón]] (1869–1929) is attributed with freeing the granaína from its rhythmic ties and making it popular.
Singers usually finish their rendering of the granaína with a ''media granaína'', a similar tune but rising to a higher pitch. [[Manuel Vallejo]] (1891–1960) was a famous exponent of this latter ''[[palo (flamenco)|cante]]''.

